# Day 06 - Search in Rotated Sorted Array

## Problem Statement
There is an integer array `nums` sorted in ascending order with distinct values. Before being passed to your function, the array may have been rotated at an unknown index.

Given the rotated sorted array `nums` and an integer `target`, return the index of `target` if it exists in the array; otherwise, return `-1`.

You must write an algorithm with **O(log n)** runtime complexity.

## Code

class Solution {
public:
    int search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int st = 0, end = n - 1;

        while (st <= end) {
            int mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] == target) {
                return mid;
            }

            else if (nums[st] <= nums[mid]) {
                if (nums[st] <= target && nums[mid] >= target) {
                    end = mid - 1;
                } else {
                    st = mid + 1;
                }
            }

            else {
                if (nums[mid] <= target && nums[end] >= target) {
                    st = mid + 1;
                } else {
                    end = mid - 1;
                }
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }
};



## Time Complexity
**O(log n)**

## Space Complexity
**O(1)**

## Approach
This solution uses a modified **Binary Search** to efficiently search in a rotated sorted array. At each iteration, we calculate the middle index and check if it contains the target. If not, we determine which half of the array is sorted. If the left half is sorted, we check whether the target lies within that range. If it does, we continue searching in the left half; otherwise, we search in the right half. Similarly, if the right half is sorted, we check whether the target lies in that range and update the search space accordingly. By eliminating half of the search space in every iteration, the algorithm achieves **O(log n)** time complexity.
